---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { absoluteUrl } from '../../i18n/utils';

const lang = 'en';
const title = 'Novel — Genesis: The Disappearance of the Founder and the Promise';
const description = 'A historical fiction about the disappearance of Satoshi Nakamoto. Built on the primary sources archived by Bitcoin Institute, the novel reads the silence of one developer and the choices he left behind.';
---

<BaseLayout
  title={`${title} - Bitcoin Institute`}
  description={description}
  lang={lang}
  alternateJa={absoluteUrl('/novel/', 'ja')}
>
  <div class="container novel-page">
    <header class="hero">
      <p class="eyebrow">Novel</p>
      <h1>Genesis<br /><span class="subtitle">— The Disappearance of the Founder and the Promise</span></h1>
      <p class="tagline">The Will Bitcoin Left Behind and the Quantum Shock</p>
    </header>

    <section class="lead">
      <p>
        Satoshi Nakamoto.<br />
        Only the name remained. No face, no voice, no nationality, not even an age.<br />
        In the spring of 2011, he vanished after leaving behind a two-line email.
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <p>I've moved on to other things.<br />It's in good hands with Gavin and everyone.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        What he left behind: a nine-page paper, roughly thirty thousand lines of C++,
        hundreds of emails and forum posts — and about 1.1 million bitcoins that have
        not moved for sixteen years.
      </p>
      <p class="inner-questions">
        — What was he thinking?<br />
        — What did he struggle with, and what did he choose?<br />
        — Why did he never speak of himself, nor show emotion?
      </p>
      <p>
        Tokyo, 2025. The story begins with three outer questions raised at a crypto conference
        — "Why 21 million?", "Why did he leave?", "Why is Bitcoin different from every
        cryptocurrency that followed?" — but what the reader actually ends up following is
        the layer beneath them: the <em>inner</em> questions of one developer.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>A developer reading a developer</h2>
      <p>
        This book is not a retelling of Bitcoin's history.<br />
        <strong>It is an attempt to read, through one developer's choices, what he was thinking</strong>
        — and the author's note says so in plain words.
      </p>
      <p>
        The author is a developer too, and that is what makes certain readings possible.
        Why was the paper cut down to nine pages? Why was a 200-byte reserved field left in place?
        Why was the hashing code deliberately left sub-optimal? Why, in the earliest commits,
        was there no version control, no issue tracker, no CI?
        Why was the last commit message not a farewell, but one quiet technical line?
      </p>
      <p>
        The novel draws on public records: the Bitcoin whitepaper, the cryptography mailing list,
        BitcoinTalk, private correspondence with Martti Malmi, Mike Hearn, Adam Back and Hal Finney,
        and the full record of <em>COPA v. Wright</em>. Emails, forum posts, commit timestamps,
        small tics of prose, the Patoshi pattern inscribed into the early blockchain — the
        verifiable fragments are read in full, and the story is written into the
        <em>space between them</em>: the thought, the hesitation, the decision of one developer.
      </p>
      <p>
        In public, Satoshi Nakamoto never showed emotion. He kept to technical discussion
        and never let a personal line slip. And yet — exactly once, he made an exception.
        The genesis block. The first block of the chain, with a <em>Times</em> headline inscribed
        into it. Why was that the one place he allowed himself to feel? This novel begins its
        reading of his <em>shape of silence</em> from that single point.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Timelines that cross</h2>
      <p>
        The narrative moves between several timelines. Each scene can be read on its own,
        but they converge, eventually, into a single line.
      </p>
      <ul class="timeline">
        <li><strong>1995</strong><span>A twelve-year-old boy loses his family to the violence of centralized power.</span></li>
        <li><strong>2007-2008</strong><span>A developer writes code for eighteen months, known to no one.</span></li>
        <li><strong>Autumn 2008</strong><span>In the middle of the Lehman collapse, a nine-page paper is dropped onto the cryptography mailing list.</span></li>
        <li><strong>January 2009</strong><span>A message is inscribed into the genesis block.</span></li>
        <li><strong>August 2010</strong><span>184 billion BTC shake the network, and an unseen attacker watches.</span></li>
        <li><strong>Spring 2011</strong><span>Satoshi leaves Mike Hearn a two-line email and disappears.</span></li>
        <li><strong>March 2024</strong><span>A London courtroom puts the "false Satoshi" on record.</span></li>
        <li><strong>2025 · Tokyo</strong><span>Misaki, a 25-year-old office worker, starts tracing the meaning of Satoshi's silence.</span></li>
        <li><strong>2041</strong><span>When AI takes hold of quantum computing, Bitcoin faces its gravest trial.</span></li>
        <li><strong>2140</strong><span>On the day the last bitcoin is mined, another message is written into the chain.</span></li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>And this archive</h2>
      <p>
        The site you are reading now — Bitcoin Institute — hosts the primary sources that the
        novel draws from.
      </p>
      <p>
        Satoshi's forum posts, his replies on the cryptography list, private emails with
        Martti Malmi and Mike Hearn, Hal Finney's "Running bitcoin," Laszlo Hanyecz's pizza
        thread, the BitcoinTalk thread on the 184 billion BTC overflow, the judgement in
        <em>COPA v. Wright</em> — all of these are reachable from the
        <a href="/entries/">entries index</a> and the
        <a href="/participants/">figures index</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        You can read the novel first and check the record afterwards, or read the record first
        and let the novel read between the lines. From either direction, the shape of one
        <em>question</em> — what was Satoshi Nakamoto thinking — comes slowly into view.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>About the book</h2>
      <p>
        Author: Shinji Kashihara<br />
        Original language: Japanese (English edition available)<br />
        Published: 2025
      </p>
      <p class="note">
        This work is historical fiction. Dates, quotations, figures, technical specifications,
        and statements attributed to real people as <em>historical fact</em> have been checked
        against public records. Interior monologue, motivations and scene-level detail are
        filled in as fiction.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="buy">
      <h2>Where to read</h2>
      <p class="buy-lead">
        Available on Amazon. <strong>Kindle editions are free to read for
        <a href="https://www.amazon.com/kindle-dbs/hz/signup" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Kindle Unlimited</a> subscribers.</strong>
      </p>
      <ul class="buy-links">
        <li>
          <a href="https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B0GCSLMSWT" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            <span class="edition">English Edition (Kindle)</span>
            <span class="ku-badge">Free with Kindle Unlimited</span>
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B0GDFZNBLK" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            <span class="edition">English Edition (Paperback)</span>
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B0G6MCVMGX" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            <span class="edition">Japanese Edition (Kindle)</span>
            <span class="ku-badge">Free with Kindle Unlimited</span>
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B0GDDL1634" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            <span class="edition">Japanese Edition (Paperback)</span>
          </a>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .novel-page {
    max-width: 720px;
  }
  .hero {
    text-align: center;
    padding: 2.5rem 0 2rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }
  .hero .eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.2em;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
  }
  .hero h1 {
    font-size: 2.2rem;
    line-height: 1.25;
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
  }
  .hero .subtitle {
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    font-weight: normal;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }
  .hero .tagline {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    margin: 0;
  }
  .lead {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
  }
  .lead blockquote {
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    padding: 0.25rem 1rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-style: italic;
  }
  .lead blockquote p {
    margin: 0.25rem 0;
  }
  .lead .inner-questions {
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
    margin: 1.75rem 0;
    padding: 0.5rem 1rem;
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.95;
  }
  section {
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }
  section h2 {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    padding-bottom: 0.4rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  .timeline {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .timeline li {
    padding: 0.5rem 0;
    border-bottom: 1px dashed var(--color-border);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }
  .timeline li:last-child {
    border-bottom: none;
  }
  .timeline strong {
    display: inline-block;
    min-width: 10em;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }
  .note {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    border-left: 2px solid var(--color-border);
    padding-left: 0.75rem;
  }
  .buy {
    background: var(--color-bg-muted, rgba(0,0,0,0.02));
    padding: 1.5rem;
    border-radius: 4px;
  }
  .buy-lead {
    margin-top: 0;
  }
  .buy-links {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0.5rem 0 0;
    display: grid;
    gap: 0.5rem;
  }
  .buy-links a {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    background: var(--color-bg);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 4px;
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .buy-links a:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }
  .buy-links .ku-badge {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    padding: 0.15rem 0.55rem;
    border-radius: 999px;
    background: var(--color-accent);
    color: var(--color-bg);
    white-space: nowrap;
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }
  .buy-lead strong a {
    color: inherit;
    text-decoration: underline;
  }
  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .hero h1 {
      font-size: 1.7rem;
    }
    .hero .subtitle {
      font-size: 1rem;
    }
    .timeline strong {
      display: block;
      min-width: auto;
      margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
    }
  }
</style>
